# Palomar Observatory: A Beacon of Astronomical Discovery

For the instrumental track, see [Declaration of Conformity (Wellwater Conspiracy album)](/Declaration_of_Conformity_(Wellwater_Conspiracy_album)).

## Observatory Overview

**Palomar Observatory**, a premier astronomical research facility, stands majestically in the [Palomar Mountains](/Palomar_Mountain) of [San Diego County, California](/San_Diego_County,_California), United States. Owned and operated by the [California Institute of Technology](/California_Institute_of_Technology) (Caltech), the observatory has been a cornerstone of astronomical research since its inception. Research time at Palomar is granted to Caltech and its research partners, which include the [Jet Propulsion Laboratory](/Jet_Propulsion_Laboratory) (JPL), [Yale University](/Yale_University), and the [National Astronomical Observatories of China](/National_Astronomical_Observatories_of_China).

## Telescopes and Instruments

Palomar Observatory is home to several cutting-edge telescopes, each contributing uniquely to the field of astronomy:

- **Hale Telescope**: The 200-inch (5.1 m) [Hale Telescope](/Hale_Telescope) is the crown jewel of Palomar Observatory. It was the largest telescope in the world from 1949 until 1975, when the Russian [BTA-6](/BTA-6) telescope saw [first light](/First_light_(astronomy)). The Hale Telescope has been instrumental in numerous discoveries, including [quasars](/Quasar) and the study of [stellar nucleosynthesis](/Stellar_nucleosynthesis).

- **Samuel Oschin Telescope**: The 48-inch (1.2 m) [Samuel Oschin telescope](/Samuel_Oschin_telescope) is dedicated to the [Zwicky Transient Facility](/Zwicky_Transient_Facility) (ZTF). It has been pivotal in the discovery of [dwarf planets](/Dwarf_planet) such as [Eris](/Eris_(dwarf_planet)) and [Sedna](/90377_Sedna).

- **Palomar 60-inch Telescope**: The 60-inch (1.5 m) telescope operates fully robotically and has been crucial in the discovery of the first [brown dwarf](/Brown_dwarf). It currently hosts the SED Machine [integral field spectrograph](/Integral_field_spectrograph) instrument used as part of [ZTF](/Zwicky_Transient_Facility) transient followup and classification.

- **Gattini-IR Telescope**: The 30-centimetre (12-inch) [Gattini-IR](/Gattini-IR) telescope is designed for near-infrared observations, contributing to the study of transient astronomical events.

## History

### Hale's Vision for Large Telescopes

The visionary behind Palomar Observatory, astronomer [George Ellery Hale](/George_Ellery_Hale), was renowned for building the world's largest telescope four times in succession. In 1928, Hale published an article proposing the 200-inch Palomar reflector, inviting the American public to learn about how large telescopes could help answer fundamental questions about the universe. Hale followed this article with a letter to the International Education Board of the [Rockefeller Foundation](/Rockefeller_Foundation) dated April 16, 1928, requesting funding for this ambitious project. In his letter, Hale stated:

> "No method of advancing science is so productive as the development of new and more powerful instruments and methods of research. A larger telescope would not only furnish the necessary gain in light space-penetration and photographic resolving power, but permit the application of ideas and devices derived chiefly from the recent fundamental advances in physics and chemistry."

### Hale Telescope

The 200-inch telescope is named after astronomer and telescope builder [George Ellery Hale](/George_Hale). It was built by Caltech with a $6 million grant from the Rockefeller Foundation, using a [Pyrex](/Pyrex) blank manufactured by [Corning Glass Works](/Corning_Glass_Works) under the direction of George McCauley. [Dr. J.A. Anderson](/John_August_Anderson) was the initial project manager, assigned in the early 1930s. The telescope saw [first light](/First_light_(astronomy)) on January 26, 1949, targeting [NGC 2261](/NGC_2261). The American astronomer [Edwin Powell Hubble](/Edwin_Powell_Hubble) was the first astronomer to use the telescope.

### Architecture and Design

The [Art Deco](/Art_Deco) architecture of the Observatory's buildings, including the dome of the 200-inch Hale Telescope, was developed by [Russell W. Porter](/Russell_W._Porter). Porter was also responsible for much of the technical design of the Hale Telescope and Schmidt Cameras, producing a series of cross-section engineering drawings. Porter worked on the designs in collaboration with many engineers and Caltech committee members. [Max Mason](/Max_Mason) directed the construction, and [Theodore von Karman](/Theodore_von_Karman) was involved in the engineering.

